Project 2: Ec2 as a File Server(With EBS volume)

This will allow you to uplaod files like PDF's ,images,zip files into Ec2  and allow
users to downlaod them from their browser 

 Project Architecture:

Ec2 Instance
    |
Extra EBS volume
    |
Mounted at /mnt/files
    |
Served via Ngnix /files/


Step 1 : Create and Attach the EBS volume to the Instance 
------------------------------------------------------------
In AWS console: 
1.Go to the Ec2 section -> There go to the Elasit Block Store -> Inside it click on the Volumes
2.Click Create volume 
3.Choose:
     type : gp3
     size : 5 GB
     AZ   : Must match the instance AZ
4.After creatiion -> Attach Volume
  *Select the Ec2 Instance 
  *Device name will appear as: 
   /dev/sdf -> Ec2 maps it to /dev/xvdf usually   
You can attach a volume to a instance even when its stopped 

Step 2: Check if Ec2 detects the volume
-------------------------------------------------------------
1.SSH into the instance  and run 
  >> lsblk

If you see the new volume then its good but if don't see its not attached 

Step 3 - Format the new EBS volume 
--------------------------------------------------------------
Format as ext4:
>> sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdf
Once formatted ,create a folder where you will mount it: 
>> sudo mkdir /mnt/files
Mount the EBS volume
>> sudo mount /dev/xvdf/ /mnt/files

Test if mounted or not :
>> df -h 

Step 5 - Give permission so you can place files
-----------------------------------------------------------
>> sudo chown ubuntu:ubuntu /mnt/files
Now you can upload files here 

To make it autoremount after restart use the following steps: 
First Get the UUID
>> blkid    #copy the blockid 

Paste that UUID in this file with this following command 
>> sudo nano /etc/fstab
Add this line :
UUID=xxxx-xxxx  /mnt/files  ext4  defaults,nofail  0  2

Save and test:
** >> sudo mount -a 
If no error ->>  SUCCESS

Step 7 - Serve file using Nignx
-----------------------------------------------------------
Edit default site config : 
>> sudo nano /etc/ngixn/sites-enabled/default

find the server block and add  this :

location /files/ {
  alias /mnt/files/;
  autoindex on;  #show all files in browssers
}
Save and restart the nginx 

To test wheather the nginx file has any error use the following command :
>> sudo nginx -t 
And then restart it
>> sudo systemctl restart nginx

Step 8 - Test Your file server 
---------------------------------------------------------
Uplaod any files: 
>> echo "hello amith" > /mnt/files/test.txt
Open this in browser: 
>> http://ec2-public-ip/files/test.txt
You'll see your file 

Upload more file and check  using this URL you will see something like this:
>> http://ec2-public-ip/files


